A change in LPS activity is expected to alter the distribution of monsoon precipitation. The climatological precipitation is strong over the BoB and into central India along the typical LPS trajectory (
 Fig. 4
  A
 ). The climatology of precipitation related to LPS originating in the BoB shows that those storms contribute to both continental and oceanic rainfall (
 Fig. 4
  B
 ). The LPS originating over land contribute more to continental rainfall, especially in the northern parts of India (
 Fig. 4
  C
 ). These patterns of LPS-related rainfall illustrate the importance of these storms for the hydrology of India and the Himalaya. The projected changes in seasonal mean rainfall show a significant drying over the BoB (
 Fig. 4
  A
 ). The component of precipitation associated with the BoB storms declines substantially, consistent with the decrease in LPS genesis over the BoB (
 Fig. 4
  B
 ). The contribution of LPS of continental origin to seasonal mean rainfall increases in the future projection (
 Fig. 4
  C
 ).
